---
import Base from '../layouts/Base.astro';
import Diagnostic from '../components/Diagnostic.astro';
import { SITE, breadcrumb, faqPage, orgId, personId } from '../lib/site';
import { QUESTIONS } from '../lib/diagnostic';

const path = '/ai-project-risk-diagnostic';
const title = 'AI project risk diagnostic: free, ungated, sourced | implementai.today';
const description =
  'A free diagnostic that checks your AI project against the factors named in the published research. Eight questions, each linked to the study behind it. Not a validated model. No sign-up, nothing stored.';

const qa = [
  {
    q: 'Is this a validated statistical model?',
    a: 'No. It cannot predict whether your project will fail and it does not try. It is a structured way to check a project against factors that named studies measured or identified. The weights are a judgement about risk ordering, not a finding from any study.',
  },
  {
    q: 'What does the diagnostic measure?',
    a: 'Eight factors: where the project came from, whether a business metric with a baseline exists, whether the data exists and is reachable, who owns the system after launch, whether it changes existing daily work, whether there is a funded route to production, whether you are buying or building bespoke, and whether spending is capped and alerted.',
  },
  {
    q: 'Is it free, and do I have to sign up?',
    a: 'It is free and there is no sign-up. Nothing is stored and nothing is sent anywhere. The scoring runs entirely in your browser.',
  },
  {
    q: 'Why should I trust the questions?',
    a: 'Each question shows the study it comes from and links to it. Where a study is a forecast rather than a measurement, or blocks automated readers, we say so on the source itself.',
  },
];

const schema = [
  breadcrumb([
    { name: 'Home', path: '/' },
    { name: 'AI project risk diagnostic', path },
  ]),
  faqPage(qa),
  {
    '@type': 'WebApplication',
    '@id': `${SITE.url}${path}#app`,
    name: 'AI project risk diagnostic',
    url: `${SITE.url}${path}`,
    applicationCategory: 'BusinessApplication',
    operatingSystem: 'Web browser',
    browserRequirements: 'Requires JavaScript for scoring. The questions and their sources render without it.',
    isAccessibleForFree: true,
    offers: { '@type': 'Offer', price: '0', priceCurrency: 'GBP' },
    description:
      'Checks an AI project against risk factors identified in published research from RAND, Gartner, MIT and McKinsey. Explicitly not a validated statistical model and it does not predict failure.',
    featureList: [
      'Eight factors drawn from published studies',
      'Every question links to the study behind it',
      'No sign-up, no data storage, scoring runs in the browser',
    ],
    author: { '@id': personId },
    publisher: { '@id': orgId },
  },
];
---

<Base title={title} description={description} path={path} schema={schema}>
  <div class="mx-auto max-w-6xl px-4 pt-8">
    <nav aria-label="Breadcrumb">
      <ol class="flex flex-wrap items-center gap-2 text-xs" style="font-family: var(--font-mono); color: var(--color-muted)">
        <li><a href="/" style="color: var(--color-muted)">Home</a></li>
        <li aria-hidden="true">/</li>
        <li aria-current="page">AI project risk diagnostic</li>
      </ol>
    </nav>
  </div>

  <div class="mx-auto max-w-3xl px-4 py-10">
    <p class="overline">Free. Ungated. Nothing stored.</p>
    <h1 class="mt-3">AI project risk diagnostic</h1>

    <p class="lead mt-5">
      Eight questions about your project, each one asked because a named study measured or identified
      that factor. You get a risk-factor load, the failure modes your answers point to, and the
      research behind each. It will not tell you whether your project will fail, because nothing can.
    </p>

    <p class="mt-4 text-sm" style="color: var(--color-muted)">
      The questions below, and the study behind every one of them, are the useful part. They work
      whether or not you ever press the button.
    </p>

    <hr class="my-10" style="border: 0; border-top: 1px solid var(--color-hairline)" />

    <Diagnostic />

    <section class="prose mt-20">
      <h2>How the scoring works, in full</h2>
      <p>
        Each answer carries a weight from <span class="num">0</span> to <span class="num">3</span>.
        The score is the sum of your answers as a percentage of the maximum
        <span class="num">{QUESTIONS.length * 3}</span>. A failure mode is shown when any of the
        questions that trigger it was answered at weight <span class="num">2</span> or above, and the
        three with the most triggers are displayed.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>The weights are ours, not the studies'.</strong> No published research assigns a risk
        weight to "a committee owns it" versus "one named person owns it". The studies establish that
        these factors matter. The ordering of severity is a judgement, and you should feel free to
        disagree with it. We publish the rule so you can.
      </p>
      <p>
        There is no hidden model, no calibration data, and no benchmark population. Calling this
        output a probability would be a lie, so we call it a risk-factor load: the proportion of the
        documented risk conditions your project currently carries.
      </p>

      <h2>Why it is not gated</h2>
      <p>
        The nearest comparable resources put a spreadsheet behind an email form. That is a lead-capture
        mechanism wearing a tool's clothing, and the audience for this material has learned to read it
        that way. We have nothing to sell you, so there is nothing to gate.
      </p>

      <h2>Questions, answered</h2>
      {
        qa.map(({ q, a }) => (
          <div class="mt-8">
            <h3>{q}</h3>
            <p class="mt-2">{a}</p>
          </div>
        ))
      }

      <hr class="my-10" style="border: 0; border-top: 1px solid var(--color-hairline)" />
      <p class="text-sm" style="color: var(--color-muted)">{SITE.disclosure}</p>
      <p class="text-sm">
        Next: <a href="/ai-project-failure-rate">what the failure rate actually is</a>, and which of
        the numbers you have seen were never published by anyone.
      </p>
    </section>
  </div>
</Base>
